Durban - A fishing boat had to be towed ashore after experiencing mechanical problems in Shelly Beach on Wednesday. Shelly Beach is a coastal town in Ugu District Municipality in the KwaZulu-Natal province of South Africa. Jeremiah Jackson, NSRI Shelly Beach station commander, said at 15h40 NSRI Station 20 Shelly Beach duty crew launched the sea rescue craft Spirit of Dawn to rendezvous with a recreational fishing boat reporting a motor mechanical failure of one motor. Jackson said on arrival at the scene a crewman of the casualty boat was transferred onto the sea rescue craft. To view this video please enable JavaScript, and consider upgrading to a web browser that
    supports HTML5 video This is a modal window. Beginning of dialog window. Escape will cancel and close the window. End of dialog window.  The NSRI crew were transferred onto the casualty craft where repairs to the motor were attempted. Jackson said the motor could not be repaired. The NSRI decided to tow the casualty boat safely ashore. On Wednesday night, in Cape Town, it is believed that the sighting of a shooting star passing close over the Cape Peninsula was mistaken for distress flares out at sea by residents. Daily News